---

Remove the root from the @spring onion{3} and thinly slice. Peel and finely grate the
@ginger{1} and @garlic clove{1}(finely grated) (or use a #garlic press{}). Zest the
@lime{1} and cut in half. Remove the ends from the @carrot{1}(coarsely grated)
(no need to peel!). Roughly chop the @coriander{10}(roughly chopped, stalks and all).
Boil your #kettle{}.

Put the @rice noodles{100} in a #bowl{}. Pour enough boiling water over the noodles to
completely submerge them, then cover with #clingfilm{} or a #plate{}. Leave to the
side for ~{8-10%minutes} before draining in a #colander{}. TIP: Check the noodles are
soft enough to eat before draining. If not, just leave them in the hot water for
~{2%minutes} longer. Once drained, rinse under a cold tap, put back into the bowl
and cover with cold water.

Pop the @British pork mince{240%g} into a #mixing bowl{} and add half the spring
onion, half the ginger, half the garlic and all the lime zest. Add a quarter of the
@soy sauce{50}, all the @panko breadcrumbs{15%g} and mix well to combine. Shape the
mixture into four meatballs per person.

> IMPORTANT: Remember to wash your hands and equipment after handling raw meat!

Heat a drizzle of @oil{a drizzle} in a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat. Add
the meatballs and fry until browned all over, turning occasionally, ~{8-10%minutes}.
Once the meatballs are browned, add the remaining spring onion, ginger and garlic
along with the @sugar snap peas{150%g}(trimmed) and carrot, then stir-fry everything
for ~{1%minute}.

> IMPORTANT: The meatballs are cooked when they are no longer pink in the middle.

Drain the noodles. Add the @ketjap manis{50} and remaining soy sauce to the meatballs
in the pan, stir and simmer for ~{2-3%minutes}, then tip in the noodles and half the
coriander. Squeeze in the juice from half the lime. Toss to combine and heat until
the noodles are piping hot, ~{2-3%minutes}. Taste and season with @?black pepper{}
if you feel it needs it.

Serve the noodles and meatballs in bowls and sprinkle over the rest of the coriander
and the @salted peanuts{25%g}. Serve with a wedge of the remaining lime (for anyone
that likes things extra zesty). Enjoy!